name "sec:IO system"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input/output (IO) matrix organizes market clearing conditions, equating
 demand and supply of goods and services.
 We follow the National Accounting classification where aggregate demand
 consists of intermediate inputs in production, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, private consumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, government consumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, investment, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, and exports, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Demand is met by domestic production, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, and imports, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 In current prices
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For ease of notation we omit deflators for this equation i.e.
 we write 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}^{Y}Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 etc.
\end_layout

\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y+M=R+C+G+I+X\label{eq:goods_clearing}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The right hand side objects in equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:goods_clearing"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) are aggregated from various demand side compositions, investment differs
 according to the type of capital good for example.
 Each demand object (
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

,etc) combines inputs from potentially all sectors, and from both domestic
 production and imports.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The IO system can be viewed as a retailer buying domestic production and
 imports and selling intermediate product bundles to the demand side under
 perfect competition.
 The final demand products are produced with a nested production function.
 There are two nests.
 The lower nest is between imports, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{d.s,t}$
\end_inset

, and domestic input, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{d.s,t}$
\end_inset

, from a specific sector.
 The upper nest is between aggregates of foreign and domestic inputs, 
\begin_inset Formula $YM_{d.s,t}$
\end_inset

, from the different sectors.
 The elasticity of substitution in all the upper nests is 0, but in the
 lower nest between imports and domestic production most elasticities are
 non-zero.
\end_layout

