name "subsec:IO prices"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Markets really exist only at the bottom of the CES trees, and thus this
 is where equilibrium prices are determined.
 All other prices are constructed from these equilibirum prices.
 In MAKRO the most disaggregate production level is the sectoral level,
 indexed 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 All output from a sector 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 has the same price (before taxes) irrespective of who buys it.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the input/output matrix from the national accounts, it is possible to
 derive prices for the different IO cells.
 In these cells, the net price from each delivering sector will vary.
 We disregard this information to make the model more tractable.
 In the ADAM model, prices are not explicitly defined for the IO cells.
 Instead, they use constant IO coefficients in determining the aggregate
 price, which implicitly assumes all output from sector 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 has the same price irrespective of who buys it.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The after-tax price may vary depending on the buyer, as indirect taxes can
 vary across demand components.
 For example, households generally face higher indirect taxes on private
 consumption than firms on intermediate inputs.
 Demand prices (paid by the buyer) are given by: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau}=\left(1+\tau_{d,s,t}^{Y}\right)P_{s,t}^{Y}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
