\begin_layout Subsection
Demand trees
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:IO equations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each demanded product, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{d,t}=[R_{r,t},C_{c,t},G_{g,t},I_{i,t},X_{x,t}]$
\end_inset

, is a composition of different inputs produced in different sectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, either domestically (
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

) or imported 
\begin_inset Formula $(M)$
\end_inset

 .
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that for intermediate inputs, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{r,t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is an alias for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 exists for all sectors.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The explicit problem of the zero-profit retailer selling an aggregated final
 product to a specific market, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{d,t}$
\end_inset

, is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
\max_{Y_{d,st},M_{d,st}}\Pi_{d,t}^{retailer}=P_{d,t}^{D}D_{d,t}-\sum_{s}\left(P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau}Y_{d,s,t}+P_{d,s,t}^{M\tau}M_{d,s,t}\right)\\
\\
\text{s.t. }D_{d,t}=\text{Leontief}\left(YM_{d,s1,t},...,\text{\ensuremath{YM_{d,S,t}}}\right)\\
\\
\text{s.t. }YM_{d,s,t}=CES\left(Y_{d,s,t},M_{d,s,t}\right)\\
\\
\text{s.t. }P_{d,t}^{D}D_{d,t}=\sum_{s}\left(P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau}Y_{d,s,t}+P_{d,s,t}^{M\tau}M_{d,s,t}\right)\\
\\
\end{array}\label{eq:retailer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $YM_{d,s,t}$
\end_inset

 is a CES bundle over domestic and foreign inputs, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{d,s,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{d,s,t}$
\end_inset

.
 The last equation in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:retailer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is the perfect competition condition that gives the final product price,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{d,t}^{D}$
\end_inset

.
 Given the perfect competition condition this additive separable problem
 can be split into two cost minimization problems for a given level of demand
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{d,t}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\text{min}_{YM_{d,s,t}}\sum_{s}P_{d,s,t}^{YM}\cdot YM_{d,s,t}\\
\\
\text{s.t. }D_{d,t}=\text{Leontief}\left(YM_{d,s1,t},...,YM_{d,S,t}\right)\\
\\
\text{s.t. }P_{d,t}^{D}D_{d,t}=\sum_{s}P_{d,s,t}^{YM}\cdot YM_{d,s,t}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\text{min}_{Y_{d,s,t},M_{d,s,t}}P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau}Y_{d,s,t}+P_{d,s,t}^{M\tau}M_{d,s,t}\\
\\
\text{s.t. }YM_{d,s,t}=CES\left(Y_{d,s,t},M_{d,s,t}\right)\\
\\
\text{s.t. }P_{d,t}^{YM}\cdot YM_{d,t}=P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau}Y_{d,s,t}+P_{d,s,t}^{M\tau}M_{d,s,t}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above structure does not apply for exports and inventory investments.
 For exports there are explicit demands for domestic exports and for imports
 for export - the two are not nested (see exports chapter).
 For inventory investments there is no aggregated demand for inventory investmen
ts, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{iL,t}$
\end_inset

.
 Aggregate inventory investments is simply an accounting quantity imputed
 using chain indices.
 The real demand is for sectoral inventory investments, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{iL,s,t}$
\end_inset

.
 Determination of inputs to exports and inventory investments have their
 own subsections below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aggregation of foreign and domestic inputs
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-bottom"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Domestic and foreign inputs are aggregated using a CES function with a fixed
 elasticity of substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\equiv\eta_{d,s}^{YM}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
YM_{d,s,t}=\left[\left(\mu_{d,s,t}^{Y}\right)^{\frac{1}{\eta}}\left(Y_{d,s,t}\right)^{\frac{\eta-1}{\eta}}+\left(\mu_{d,s,t}^{M}\right)^{\frac{1}{\eta}}\left(M_{d,s,t}\right)^{\frac{\eta-1}{\eta}}\right]^{\frac{\eta}{\eta-1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is equivalent to solving an optimization problem with the accounting
 identity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d,s,t}^{YM}\cdot YM_{d,s,t}=P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau}Y_{d,s,t}+P_{d,s,t}^{M\tau}M_{d,s,t}
\]

\end_inset

which generates the demand functions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{d,s,t}=\mu_{d,s,t}^{y}\cdot YM_{d,s,t}\cdot\left(\frac{P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau}}{P_{d,s,t}^{YM}}\right)^{-\eta_{d,s}^{YM}}\label{eq:retailer_ces1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{d,s,t}=\mu_{d,s,t}^{m}\cdot YM_{d,s,t}\cdot\left(\frac{P_{d,s,t}^{M\tau}}{P_{d,s,t}^{YM}}\right)^{-\eta_{d,s}^{YM}}\label{eq:retailer_ces2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{d,s,t}^{YM}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding zero-profit CES price aggregate of prices 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau},P_{d,s,t}^{M\tau}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key implication of using this CES structure to aggregate the quantities
 from foreign and domestic suppliers (instead of a price/quantity index
 construction often used in the data) is that it contains behavior which
 can be quantified through the elasticity parameter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Reduced short-run elasticity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We tweak the structure above (subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-bottom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) in order to impose lower short-run (relative to long run) elasticities
 between domestic and foreign inputs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specifically, we retain the zero profit condition along with the explicit
 quantity aggregator as before:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d,s,t}^{YM}\cdot YM_{d,s,t}=P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau}Y_{d,s,t}+P_{d,s,t}^{M\tau}M_{d,s,t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
YM_{d,s,t}=\left[\left(\mu_{d,s,t}^{Y}\right)^{\frac{1}{\eta}}\left(Y_{d,s,t}\right)^{\frac{\eta-1}{\eta}}+\left(\mu_{d,s,t}^{M}\right)^{\frac{1}{\eta}}\left(M_{d,s,t}\right)^{\frac{\eta-1}{\eta}}\right]^{\frac{\eta}{\eta-1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But, replace the ratio of the two demand equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{M_{d,s,t}}{Y_{d,s,t}}=\frac{\mu_{d,s,t}^{m}}{\mu_{d,s,t}^{y}}\cdot\left(\frac{P_{d,s,t}^{M\tau}}{P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau}}\right)^{-\eta_{d,s}^{YM}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with an ad-hoc generalization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{M_{d,s,t}}{Y_{d,s,t}}=\frac{\mu_{d,s,t}^{m}}{\mu_{d,s,t}^{y}}\cdot\left(R_{d,s,t}^{YM}\right)^{-\eta_{d,s}^{YM}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the relative price object, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{d,s,t}^{YM}$
\end_inset

, reacts sluggishly to changes in actual prices:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{d,s,t}^{YM}=\left(R_{d,s,t-1}^{YM}\right)^{\lambda_{d,s}}\left(\frac{P_{d,s,t}^{M\tau}}{P_{d,s,t}^{Y\tau}}\right)^{1-\lambda_{d,s}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resulting price 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{d,s,t}^{YM}$
\end_inset

 is no longer the standard CES price, but it remains the price consistent
 with zero profits.
 It is still a method of aggregation, except with added behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aggregation of quantities from different sectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this level we use a Leontief aggregator combining sectoral inputs into
 final goods in fixed proportions.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in\{c,k,g,r\}$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
YM_{d,s,t}=\mu_{d,s,t}^{YM}D_{d,t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{d,s,t}^{YM}\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 are the Leontief shares and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{d,t}$
\end_inset

 are the final goods quantities.
 For example 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{c,s,t}^{YM}$
\end_inset

 is the fraction of total demand for consumption good 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{c,t}$
\end_inset

, that falls on goods produced or imported by sector 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that for intermediate goods, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{r,t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is an alias for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 exists for all sectors.
 Finally, note that for investments we assume that all investment demand
 is made up of the same composition of sectoral inputs across sectors, implying
 that all sectors have identical investment prices.
 In national accounts, the price of investments may differ between sectors.
 Therefore, to ensure consistency with national accounts, we introduce a
 correction parameter in Appendix 
