LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Sectoral investments"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The parameter has a linear effect on aggregate prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exports
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For exports there are explicit separate demand functions for domestically
 produced exports and imports that are re-exported.
 Domestically produced exports, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{x,t}^{Y}$
\end_inset

, and imports for export, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{x,t}^{M}$
\end_inset

, are each determined by Armington demand relations - see the exports chapter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each export demand, sectoral inputs are combined with a Leontief aggregator.
 The inputs are given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{x,s,t}=\mu_{x,s,t}^{Xy}\cdot X_{x,t}^{Y}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{x,s,t}=\mu_{x,s,t}^{Xm}\cdot X_{x,t}^{M}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Aggregation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:IO aggregates"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The production of each sector is the sum of deliveries to all demand components
 for both domestic production and imports:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{s,t}=\underset{d}{\sum}Y_{d,s,t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{s,t}=\underset{d}{\sum}M_{d,s,t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the sectoral level, there are model-defined equilibrium prices.
 However, at the aggregate level there are no model-defined prices.
 Thus, for totals to ensure consistency with National Accounts we use Paasche
 price indices and Laspeyres indices for the corresponding quantities.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We do the same for GDP and for aggregate gross value added.
 Note that housing and non-housing consumption do not face this problem
 as they have model-defined aggregate prices through CES preferences.
 Investment quantities aggregate linearly so that we do not need a price
 index to calculate the price of total investment of a given type (structures
 or equipment).
 Using the price index approach does not affect the outcome in a significant
 way.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In particular, for a given variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=[C,I,G,R,X,M]$
\end_inset

, we use the identity
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{t}^{Z}Z_{t}=\sum_{d}P_{d,t}^{Z}Z_{d,t}\label{eq:price_sum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the index relationship
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{t-1}^{Z}Z_{t}=\sum_{d}P_{d,t-1}^{Z}Z_{d,t}\label{index_rel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Together, (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:price_sum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "index_rel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) imply the price and quantity dynamic indices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{t}=Z_{t-1}\frac{\sum_{d}P_{d,t-1}^{Z}Z_{d,t}}{\sum_{d}P_{d,t-1}^{Z}Z_{d,t-1}}\;\;\text{and}\;\;P_{t}^{Z}=P_{t-1}^{Z}\frac{\sum_{d}P_{d,t}^{Z}Z_{d,t}}{\sum_{d}P_{d,t-1}^{Z}Z_{d,t}}
\]

\end_inset

Price indices are unnecessary when quantities are homogeneous.
 In such a case, we replace the index equation with the quantity sum and
 work with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{t}^{Z}Z_{t}=\sum_{d}P_{d,t}^{Z}Z_{d,t}\;\;\text{and}\;\;Z_{t}=\sum_{d}Z_{d,t}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

